<HEAD>Sultan Of Brunei Denies Role in House of Fraser Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sultan of Brunei on Friday denied any role in
the $1 billion takeover of Harrods owner House of Fraser PLC by the
Al-Fayed brothers in 1985.
   The sultan said in a statement that he had no part in the
takeover, nor did he provide funds to Mohamed, Salah and Ali
Al-Fayed to help them buy it.
   The ruler of Brunei acknowledged that a power of attorney
privilege was granted to Mohamed Al-Fayed to buy the Dorchester
Hotel for the sultan.
   If this privilege was used for something else, it was done so
totally without the sultan's authority or knowledge, the statement
said.
   On Wednesday, the government released a report by Department of
Trade and Industry inspectors saying the Al-Fayeds lied about their
wealth and background to succeed with the bid and that it was
likely they used their association with the sultan to enable them
to obtain funds toward the takeover.
   They said they believed the Al-Fayeds did not have enough money
of their own to buy the retailing group.
   ``The evidence pointing to Brunei is very strong indeed,'' the
report said, ``and we have conveyed our findings to the sultan. Our
views stand.''
   The Al-Fayeds deny they misled anyone and maintain that they
paid for House of Fraser with their own cash.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said Tuesday he would not seek
disqualification of any of the company's directors.
   The Serious Fraud Office and the Director of the Public
Prosecutions announced last week they would not pursue a criminal
prosecution in connection with the takeover.
</TEXT>
