NICARAGUA (NU)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Elliott Abrams, the State Department's top
officer for Central America in the mid-1980s, admitted in
federal court to withholding information from Congress
regarding secret White House efforts at the time to arm
anti-Sandinista guerrillas in Nicaragua.
   Mr. Abrams, a former assistant secretary of state, pleaded
guilty to two misdemeanor charges as part of an agreement
under which he must cooperate in a continuing investigation
of the Iran-Contra affair by Independent Counsel Lawrence
Walsh.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Craig Gillen, Mr. Walsh's associate counsel who
represented the prosecutor at the court proceedings, was
cautious in assessing Mr. Abrams's value to the inquiry. But
as a senior Reagan administration official, Mr. Abrams moved
in high circles and could shed light on the activities of
White House and Central Intelligence Agency officers in
connection with the same covert supply network.
   Duane Clarridge, a Central Intelligence Agency officer who
had been closely involved in the anti-Sandinista war, has
been identified as a target of Mr. Walsh's inquiry. And the
prosecutor has given immunity to a former associate of Donald
Gregg, a national security adviser to then-Vice President
Bush and now U.S. ambassador to South Korea.
   The charges against Mr. Abrams, which carry a maximum
penalty of one year in prison for each count, are themselves
the product of an earlier agreement in which Mr. Walsh's
office won the cooperation of Alan Fiers, who headed the
CIA's Central America task force in the mid-80s. Mr. Fiers
also pleaded guilty to withholding information from Congress,
and his testimony was instrumental in the case against Mr.
Abrams and in the more serious perjury charges brought last
month against the CIA's former operations chief, Clair
George.
   With his hands clasped behind his back, the 43-year-old
Mr. Abrams answered simply "I plead guilty" after U.S.
district Judge Aubrey Robinson read each of the counts
against him. In a brief statement later, Mr. Abrams showed
flashes of his old defiance, but he was a far more subdued
figure than the brash assistant secretary who symbolized a
generation of young neo-conservatives in the Reagan
administration. Many, like Mr. Abrams, had watched Vietnam
from academic campuses and had little patience with Congress
as they waged their proxy wars against communism from the
halls of Washington.
   A former Senate aide, Mr. Abrams infuriated Republicans
and Democrats alike in the Capitol, and yesterday's charges
focus on misleading testimony he gave in October 1986 after a
cargo plane ferrying supplies to the Contras was shot down in
Nicaragua. Appearing before Senate and House committees, Mr.
Abrams sought to distance the Reagan administration from the
supply network, and though he had directly solicited a $10
million contribution from the sultan of Brunei two months
earlier, he denied that foreign governments were helping the
Contras.
   At the time of his testimony, the administration was only
days away from overturning a ban on U.S. funding for the war.
In a statement of facts accompanying yesterday's plea
agreement, Mr. Abrams is said to have feared that this
appropriations legislation would be lost if members learned
of the network.
   As assistant secretary, his specific knowledge grew out of
a close working relationship with Mr. Fiers and Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver North, a White House aide who oversaw the supply
operation and served on a restricted interagency group headed
by Mr. Abrams.
   Beginning in 1985, the court papers said, Mr. Abrams
became "generally aware" that Col. North was working with the
Contras, and he and Mr. Fiers had specifically discussed
using the White House aide's "private benefactor" network in
July 1986 to get food to the insurgents when a government
"humanitarian" aid program ran out of funds.
   Using the pseudonym "Kennilworth," Mr. Abrams met with a
representative of the sultan of Brunei in a London park in
August that summer. The court papers show that before his
testimony in October, he was privy to subsequent State
Department cables showing that the sultan had agreed to give
$10 million and sent the money on to a Swiss bank account
that Col. North told Mr. Abrams about.
   Standing before television cameras later, Mr. Abrams
restated his guilty plea, but said the information withheld
had only to do with activities "which at that time I believed
to be proper and lawful." The former assistant secretary, the
first State Department official to be charged by Mr. Walsh,
expressed pride in his government service, but said he was
"very happy to have this entire matter at long last behind
me."
</TEXT>
</DOC>

